The Earth and the Sun are 8.3 light minutes apart. Consider the Sun-Earth reference frame, ignoring their relative motion. Event A occurs on the Earth at $t=0$, and event B on the Sun at $t=2$ minutes, where the times are given in the Sun-Earth reference frame. Find the time difference between these events according to:
(a) an observer travelling at $v = 0.8c$ from the Sun to the Earth;
(b) an observer travelling at $v = 0.8c$ in the opposite direction.

Muon is an unstable particle with a mass of 106 MeV and a mean lifetime of $2.2\,\mu\mathrm{s}$. Calculate the mean path of the muon before its decay:
(a) for a muon moving with a speed $\beta = v/c = 0.1$;
(b) for a muon moving with a speed $\bet$a = 0$.995$;
(c) for a muon with an energy of 106 GeV.
In each case, identify the approximations to be made. With the correct handling of the expression for time dilation, you would not need a calculator to obtain the numerical answers.
